## Connecting to the Robot

There are **two network modes** and **three connection tools**. Pick one of each.

### Network Modes

| Mode | What it does | Internet access |
|---|---|---|
| **AP Direct Connection** (default) | Jetson Nano generates its own Wi-Fi hotspot that your phone/laptop connects to directly  | No |
| **STA / LAN Mode** | Robot actively joins a Wi-Fi network you specify  | Yes |

Performance is identical in either mode — AP mode is recommended for general day-to-day use since it's simpler to set up. 

### Connection Tools — Which One to Use

| Tool | Type | Best for |
|---|---|---|
| **NoMachine** | Full graphical remote desktop | Jetson Nano/Orin Nano/Orin NX boards — visual, intuitive operation  |
| **VNC** | Full graphical remote desktop | Raspberry Pi 5 boards only  |
| **MobaXterm** | SSH / command-line only | Any board version — faster, lower resource usage, no desktop GUI  |

Since our unit uses the **Jetson Nano**, default tool is **NoMachine** (GUI) or **MobaXterm** (terminal/SSH — this is what we use for ROS command-line work).

### Default Login Credentials (Jetson Nano)

username: jetauto, password: hiwonder 

> ⚠️ These match the confirmed username (`jetauto`) from our existing setup — consistent with the official default.

### Default IP Addresses

| Mode | IP | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| AP Direct Connection | `192.168.149.1` | Fixed default IP when connected to the robot's own "HW" hotspot  |
| LAN Mode | Varies (e.g. `192.168.11.134`) | Assigned by your router — find it by long-pressing the robot icon in the WonderAi app  |
| USB Fixed-IP | `192.168.55.1` | Available via Micro-USB cable direct connection (Jetson boards only) — bypasses Wi-Fi entirely  |

> 📝 **Lab-specific note:** Our ROS Master URI is configured at `192.168.0.114:11311`, which means our unit is set up in **LAN mode** on the lab network, not the AP default. Confirm this IP is still current before connecting — LAN-mode IPs can change if the robot reconnects to DHCP.

### Step-by-step: Connecting via MobaXterm (SSH) — most common for our use

1. Connect your laptop to the robot's network (either the `HW...` hotspot in AP mode, or the lab Wi-Fi if in LAN mode).
2. Open MobaXterm → **Session** → choose **SSH**.
3. Enter the robot's IP (`192.168.149.1` for AP mode, or the LAN IP — e.g. `192.168.0.114` for our lab setup).
4. Select the SSH option (third option in the protocol list). 
5. Enter username in lowercase: jetauto. Press Enter, then enter password: hiwonder (password won't display as you type). 
6. You're in — you should see a terminal prompt as `jetauto@<hostname>:~$`.

### Step-by-step: Connecting via NoMachine (GUI)

1. Connect to the robot's network as above.
2. Open NoMachine → enter the robot's IP → **Configure connection to new host**.
3. Set connection name (e.g. "robot"), enter the host IP, click Add. 
4. Enter username jetauto / password hiwonder, check "Save this password", click Login. 
5. The full Jetson Nano desktop opens remotely.

